Thus, 

L. australis

sp. nov.
has three forms of microsclere: a microxea (
Fig. 3D
) with attenuating, hastate ends that is usually straight, but may be slightly curved, ranging in length from about 19–40 µm; metaster-like streptasters with heavily spined, relatively long rays (
Fig. 3E
), ranging in length from about 7–15 µm; spirasters with abundant, short, microspined rays that emanate from a long, spiral axis (
Fig. 3F
), ranging in length from about 8–14 µm.

